<h1 id="ideas-for-porting-pbp-to-go">Ideas for Porting PBP to Go</h1>
<p>I’ve written the PBP kernel in a pseudo-language and generate Python,
JS and CL. I think that if you were to point your LLM at  - <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.rt">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.rt</a>,
- <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/stock.rt">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/stock.rt</a> and
- <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/jit.rt">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/jit.rt</a> </p>
<p>and gave it the Python versions  - <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py</a>, 
- <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py</a> and 
- <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/0d.py</a>,</p>
<p>it might be able to infer the Go version.</p>
<p>Maybe you also need to give it - the Ohm grammar file <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/emit.ohm">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/emit.ohm</a>
and - the Python rewrite rules <a
href="https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/emit.ohm">https://github.com/guitarvydas/pbp-dev/blob/main/kernel/emit.ohm</a></p>
<p>I suspect that using words like “concurrent” and “process” and
“thread” might get an LLM to generate convoluted / wrong code. 0D.rt
implements its own form of multi-processing from scratch - don’t let an
LLM use preconceived ideas about what threads are. Threading needs only
10’s of lines of code - all existing thread libraries that I know of
(including Go) have turned this into a behemoth, steaming pile of
complexity.</p>
<p>If you do need to use words like these, tell the LLM to use a mutual
multi-tasking model (aka “green threads”) with NO shared memory. A lot
of the cancerous complexity growth has befallen us because of the use of
implicit memory sharing (starting with the concept of “thread safety”).
When you strip the underlying memory sharing assumption out, the code
becomes orders of magnitude simpler. The first kernel I studied was 1/2
page of assembler code.</p>
